WEBVTT

00:05.000 --> 00:09.000
Hello, my name is Vladislava Drudko.

00:09.000 --> 00:13.000
I am the Director of the Department of Program for Leadership and Personal Effectiveness,

00:13.000 --> 00:16.000
certified Master Trainer.

00:16.000 --> 00:19.000
I have 20 years of experience in business training,

00:19.000 --> 00:25.000
10 years in the position of a top manager in large financial and insurance companies.

00:25.000 --> 00:28.000
Today, as part of the program Organizational Behavior,

00:28.000 --> 00:35.000
we will consider the concept of a group and a team and group dynamics,

00:35.000 --> 00:42.000
as well as get acquainted with the stages of the development of the team and the distribution of roles in the team.

00:42.000 --> 00:48.000
Today there are a lot of disputes about what a group is and what a team is.

00:48.000 --> 00:53.000
Many believe that these concepts are very interconnected,

00:53.000 --> 00:57.000
and the group is called a team, and the team is called a group.

00:57.000 --> 01:02.000
Our task is to understand what is the difference between a group and a team.

01:02.000 --> 01:06.000
We often use these concepts as interconnected,

01:06.000 --> 01:09.000
but there is a significant difference between them.

01:09.000 --> 01:12.000
What are the similarities and differences of a team?

01:12.000 --> 01:18.000
Is it always necessary to create a team at certain stages of the development of the entire company?

01:18.000 --> 01:23.000
Or is it enough to just do a group interaction?

01:23.000 --> 01:29.000
Let's first define the concepts of a group and a team.

01:29.000 --> 01:36.000
Please pay attention to the first slide and the concept of a group given by Shine and Bennis.

01:36.000 --> 01:41.000
A group is a number of people who interact with each other,

01:41.000 --> 01:47.000
psychologically recognize each other and perceive themselves as a group.

01:48.000 --> 02:02.000
And a team is a group of people who share responsibility for the results of the organization's activities.

02:02.000 --> 02:10.000
Please pay attention to the key word that distinguishes a group from a team.

02:10.000 --> 02:15.000
This is responsibility for the results of the organization's activities.

02:16.000 --> 02:22.000
You can see the main differences between a group and a team on the suggested table.

02:22.000 --> 02:29.000
You can notice that a group from a team is separated by the size limit,

02:29.000 --> 02:40.000
common goals, role distribution, transparent and understandable interaction between team members and teamwork.

02:40.000 --> 02:46.000
Let's consider the concept of a group and a team using the example of a management company.

02:46.000 --> 02:53.000
A management company has a financial department headed by a financial inspector.

02:53.000 --> 02:59.000
This company has a relatively limited number of employees

02:59.000 --> 03:04.000
who follow a common, understandable and acceptable goal.

03:04.000 --> 03:09.000
The tasks, roles and responsibilities are clearly distributed between them.

03:09.000 --> 03:13.000
We call the financial department a team.

03:13.000 --> 03:22.000
Again, because these people are connected by a common goal, transparent communication and distributed roles.

03:22.000 --> 03:26.000
However, this financial department is part of a large management company,

03:26.000 --> 03:30.000
where there are many other departments.

03:30.000 --> 03:37.000
For example, the personnel department, the personnel department, the sales department, the selection department, and so on.

03:37.000 --> 03:44.000
The employees of each of these departments are not united by a common goal,

03:44.000 --> 03:49.000
and certain tasks are not distributed between them.

03:49.000 --> 03:55.000
They simply realize themselves as part of a whole, as part of a large organization.

03:55.000 --> 04:02.000
Therefore, we call the employees of different departments in one management company a group of people.

04:02.000 --> 04:07.000
If we go further and pay attention to the top managers,

04:07.000 --> 04:12.000
to the managers of these departments, who gather for weekly meetings,

04:12.000 --> 04:19.000
plan their work, plan their work,

04:19.000 --> 04:25.000
plan the activities of the whole organization, follow the common goal of the company.

04:25.000 --> 04:31.000
We call the top managers a group of top managers.

04:31.000 --> 04:42.000
Thus, you can learn for yourself once again that the group of top managers is distinguished by the key words.

04:42.000 --> 04:45.000
These are the following words, the following words are the following words,

04:45.000 --> 04:51.000
the following words are the following words,

04:51.000 --> 04:54.000
What do teams need?

04:54.000 --> 05:02.000
Teams are needed in those situations when a large number of work is needed.

05:02.000 --> 05:06.000
When this work is not possible for one person.

05:06.000 --> 05:13.000
Also, in the situation of uncertainty and changes, team work increases efficiency.

05:13.000 --> 05:18.000
Because when the roles are distributed and people clearly understand the goals,

05:18.000 --> 05:21.000
the stress level is noticeably reduced.

05:21.000 --> 05:29.000
This means that interpersonal communication is more transparent, more understandable, and therefore more comfortable.

05:29.000 --> 05:37.000
Let's look at the example of a team and a group on two sports teams.

05:37.000 --> 05:40.000
On a baseball team and on a basketball team.

05:40.000 --> 05:44.000
If you remember the rules of the game in a baseball team,

05:44.000 --> 05:50.000
the members of the group are relatively independent of each other and never interact together.

05:50.000 --> 05:53.000
Thus, it is a group of athletes.

05:53.000 --> 05:57.000
But in a basketball team, the rules are completely different.

05:57.000 --> 06:01.000
The members of the group constantly interact with each other on the field,

06:01.000 --> 06:04.000
run, defend, attack, score.

06:04.000 --> 06:10.000
When a new player comes out on the field, the team members must play with him.

06:10.000 --> 06:15.000
Thus, basketball is a sports team.

06:15.000 --> 06:22.000
Let's now pay attention and consider the criteria for the effectiveness of the team's activities.

06:22.000 --> 06:26.000
Please pay attention to the proposed slide.

06:27.000 --> 06:31.000
There are only five criteria for the effectiveness of the team's activities.

06:31.000 --> 06:35.000
You already know some of them.

06:35.000 --> 06:38.000
The task, planning and setting goals.

06:38.000 --> 06:42.000
If there are no clear and transparent goals in the team,

06:42.000 --> 06:47.000
if the work is not planned for the future,

06:47.000 --> 06:52.000
if the team members do not know what specific task they are performing,

06:53.000 --> 06:57.000
it reduces the effectiveness of the team's work.

06:57.000 --> 06:59.000
The roles in the team.

06:59.000 --> 07:04.000
Each member of the team understands what role he plays.

07:04.000 --> 07:07.000
We will talk about the roles a little later.

07:07.000 --> 07:10.000
The process of the team's functioning.

07:10.000 --> 07:12.000
Interpersonal relations.

07:12.000 --> 07:14.000
Relations between teams.

07:14.000 --> 07:18.000
So, the main criteria for the effectiveness of the team's activities.

07:18.000 --> 07:21.000
You can see these criteria on the proposed slide.

07:21.000 --> 07:23.000
There are only five of them.

07:23.000 --> 07:25.000
Let's briefly discuss each of them.

07:25.000 --> 07:29.000
The task, planning and setting goals.

07:29.000 --> 07:35.000
This is a very important point to create an effective team.

07:35.000 --> 07:40.000
I often go to other companies as a consultant.

07:40.000 --> 07:46.000
It is always interesting to ask a question to the employee.

07:46.000 --> 07:51.000
Why do you come to work in this particular company?

07:51.000 --> 07:57.000
70% of employees answer that they want to do anything,

07:57.000 --> 08:03.000
but not what is related to their personal goal or business organization.

08:03.000 --> 08:07.000
Anything is related to their close relationship with the company,

08:07.000 --> 08:09.000
good social status,

08:09.000 --> 08:12.000
the company has a good reputation in the market,

08:12.000 --> 08:15.000
a car is on loan, and so on.

08:15.000 --> 08:20.000
The goal for the employee, the goal and the task set

08:20.000 --> 08:24.000
is the first step to increase his motivation to work in the group.

08:24.000 --> 08:31.000
It is believed that setting goals increases the efficiency of work by 16%

08:31.000 --> 08:33.000
due to motivation.

08:33.000 --> 08:35.000
I will give you a simple example.

08:35.000 --> 08:42.000
In my training, there are participants who learn the rules of setting goals and planning.

08:42.000 --> 08:49.000
I put a trash can in front of them and ask one participant to roll up as much paper as possible

08:49.000 --> 08:51.000
and throw it into the trash can.

08:51.000 --> 08:55.000
The participant tries to crush the paper,

08:55.000 --> 08:57.000
throwing it into the trash can,

08:57.000 --> 09:00.000
not understanding what I want from him.

09:00.000 --> 09:03.000
When he finishes this work,

09:03.000 --> 09:06.000
and I notice the time before he starts throwing the paper,

09:07.000 --> 09:12.000
I ask the next participant to do the following work.

09:12.000 --> 09:19.000
In 5 minutes, after throwing the paper into the trash can,

09:19.000 --> 09:22.000
we counted the number of paper thrown, there were 15,

09:22.000 --> 09:26.000
we need to throw more than 15 papers.

09:26.000 --> 09:29.000
Guess how the second participant behaved in the training,

09:29.000 --> 09:33.000
to whom I clearly outlined the time and the number.

09:33.000 --> 09:35.000
He got a drive.

09:35.000 --> 09:41.000
He began to rush to throw as many as possible 15 rolled papers.

09:41.000 --> 09:49.000
When he really did the exercise and threw more than 15 papers into the trash can in 5 minutes.

09:49.000 --> 09:51.000
When I stopped the exercise,

09:51.000 --> 09:59.000
two participants who took part in this game were in different emotional states.

09:59.000 --> 10:03.000
Which of them was more offended by me?

10:03.000 --> 10:05.000
Of course, the first one. Why?

10:05.000 --> 10:07.000
I asked him a question.

10:07.000 --> 10:11.000
You are now in a very uncomfortable state. Why?

10:11.000 --> 10:12.000
He did not answer.

10:12.000 --> 10:15.000
Vlad, you did not set a clear goal in front of me.

10:15.000 --> 10:18.000
You did not tell me the number.

10:18.000 --> 10:21.000
And I did not understand what you wanted from me.

10:21.000 --> 10:28.000
You see, a clearly outlined goal in time, space and quantity

10:28.000 --> 10:33.000
will always motivate your employees to achieve something.

10:33.000 --> 10:39.000
Therefore, remember that one of the important criteria for effective work in a group

10:39.000 --> 10:45.000
is setting goals, planning and assigning tasks.

10:45.000 --> 10:47.000
So, the roles in the team.

10:47.000 --> 10:55.000
The roles in the team are the distribution of responsibility between the members of one team.

10:55.000 --> 11:03.000
Who, why, when, why, who is reported to, and who gives whom what tools or documents.

11:03.000 --> 11:08.000
The next criterion is the process of team functioning.

11:08.000 --> 11:15.000
At this stage, it is very important to discuss, talk to people, talk to subordinates,

11:15.000 --> 11:21.000
meet with them as often as possible and give them feedback as much as possible

11:21.000 --> 11:24.000
and ask them what is going on.

11:24.000 --> 11:32.000
The process of team functioning determines the norms of behavior of employees in one team,

11:32.000 --> 11:38.000
the type and style of decision-making, methods of motivation and punishment.

11:38.000 --> 11:42.000
As for how often you talk to your subordinates,

11:42.000 --> 11:50.000
the last and probably the most recorded answer I heard from one of the managers of the sales department

11:50.000 --> 11:52.000
was once a quarter.

11:53.000 --> 11:58.000
I asked him the next question, how effective is the sales in your department.

11:58.000 --> 12:03.000
I believe that the participant Slukavil said that it is very effective.

12:03.000 --> 12:05.000
Although, a big question arises,

12:05.000 --> 12:11.000
can a team be effective if it sees its manager once every three months?

12:11.000 --> 12:20.000
We are talking about people who wish and enjoy being in the company.

12:20.000 --> 12:26.000
We all grew up in a family, we all grew up in the environment of people,

12:26.000 --> 12:29.000
and therefore the models of human behavior are connected,

12:29.000 --> 12:33.000
no matter where he is in the organization or wherever he is,

12:33.000 --> 12:41.000
to the need and need for socializing, communication, feedback and the ability to share your feelings.

12:41.000 --> 12:47.000
If you use this policy of meeting with your subordinates once a quarter,

12:48.000 --> 12:52.000
I will also have a question for you.

12:52.000 --> 12:56.000
And the last criterion is the relationship between teams.

12:56.000 --> 13:02.000
This is a very important criterion for the effectiveness of the work of one team.

13:02.000 --> 13:03.000
Why?

13:03.000 --> 13:09.000
Today in business, very often one team within a large corporation or company

13:09.000 --> 13:14.000
greatly affects the effectiveness of the work of another team.

13:14.000 --> 13:16.000
Let's take a simple example.

13:16.000 --> 13:23.000
The sales department has clear global plans for the interception of clients and competitors.

13:23.000 --> 13:30.000
Accordingly, to implement these plans, the sales department needs a certain number of good, cool sales.

13:30.000 --> 13:35.000
The sales department is traditionally addressed to the personnel department.

13:35.000 --> 13:39.000
The personnel department has many important tasks,

13:39.000 --> 13:43.000
because each department has its own specific plans.

13:43.000 --> 13:49.000
And you know that the shortage of personnel always exists with good personnel within any company.

13:49.000 --> 13:54.000
And so the sales department is addressed to the personnel department with an application

13:54.000 --> 13:59.000
to select a certain number of sales managers with certain competencies.

13:59.000 --> 14:03.000
Accordingly, the tasks of the sales department are different,

14:03.000 --> 14:06.000
because there are many other departments.

14:06.000 --> 14:13.000
It is very important how well people communicate with each other and how well they can agree.

14:13.000 --> 14:16.000
This can also be a part of the team.

14:16.000 --> 14:24.000
Usually, in companies that pay great attention to the increase in the effectiveness of the work of employees,

14:24.000 --> 14:27.000
when new projects are created,

14:27.000 --> 14:31.000
for example, the project that I just mentioned in the sales department

14:31.000 --> 14:36.000
is a new project.

14:36.000 --> 14:43.000
Therefore, very often companies gather a team of employees of the personnel department

14:43.000 --> 14:48.000
and employees of the sales department for the so-called team building.

14:48.000 --> 14:51.000
And there they learn to live together.

14:51.000 --> 14:56.000
After they try new role models in training,

14:56.000 --> 14:59.000
build interpersonal relationships,

14:59.000 --> 15:04.000
return to their usual life, it is much easier for them to agree.

15:04.000 --> 15:09.000
Because in business there are not only formal policies and procedures,

15:09.000 --> 15:13.000
but also interpersonal communication.

15:13.000 --> 15:19.000
So, now we have considered the main criteria for the effectiveness of the team's activities.

15:19.000 --> 15:22.000
I will give you one example,

15:22.000 --> 15:27.000
which was once presented as an experiment at the University of London.

15:27.000 --> 15:32.000
The experiment was called an intergroup conference.

15:32.000 --> 15:35.000
What was done?

15:35.000 --> 15:41.000
Employees were divided into two groups of participants and a consultant was assigned to them.

15:41.000 --> 15:45.000
The consultant was not a facilitator and a leader of this group,

15:45.000 --> 15:49.000
he just observed the work and the behavior of the participants

15:49.000 --> 15:55.000
and expressed his critical and non-critical assessments to each participant.

15:55.000 --> 15:57.000
What was happening in the group?

15:57.000 --> 16:00.000
Since there was no established leader in the group,

16:00.000 --> 16:03.000
the goals and tasks were not clearly defined,

16:03.000 --> 16:05.000
why people were gathered here.

16:05.000 --> 16:08.000
The level of anxiety increased noticeably.

16:08.000 --> 16:14.000
And the behavior of people was accompanied by a very high degree of aggression,

16:14.000 --> 16:17.000
even hysterical laughter.

16:17.000 --> 16:21.000
People began to express unpleasant things to each other.

16:21.000 --> 16:25.000
Then they tried to change the consultant.

16:25.000 --> 16:29.000
And after the failed attempt to change the consultant,

16:29.000 --> 16:33.000
as usually happens in a class where there is no good teacher,

16:33.000 --> 16:36.000
employees found a release goat in the group

16:36.000 --> 16:39.000
and began to place all their aggression on this person.

16:39.000 --> 16:43.000
Therefore, part of the team just self-eliminated.

16:43.000 --> 16:46.000
Nobody wanted to be a release goat,

16:46.000 --> 16:50.000
so people just froze and did not express any emotions at all.

16:50.000 --> 16:52.000
The experiment ended there.

16:52.000 --> 16:56.000
As a result, people did everything they wanted,

16:56.000 --> 16:59.000
but did not study their own behavior.

16:59.000 --> 17:03.000
I told this example to those above-mentioned criteria,

17:03.000 --> 17:06.000
which I just commented on.

17:06.000 --> 17:10.000
It is very important that if there are no clearly defined goals,

17:10.000 --> 17:13.000
roles, tasks, and roles of the leader,

17:13.000 --> 17:16.000
we will talk about this in a separate course today,

17:16.000 --> 17:19.000
interpersonal communication will never be built.

17:19.000 --> 17:21.000
And if there are no goals in the team,

17:21.000 --> 17:24.000
and interpersonal communication is not built,

17:24.000 --> 17:26.000
it cannot be effective.

17:34.000 --> 17:37.000
So, dear, we will move on with you.

17:37.000 --> 17:41.000
We have already learned about the criteria for the effectiveness of the team's activities,

17:41.000 --> 17:46.000
and we have analyzed each of them in detail at the example of the group conference.

17:46.000 --> 17:51.000
Now we will get acquainted with what group dynamics is.

17:51.000 --> 17:56.000
The word dynamics itself is an antonym for the word static.

17:56.000 --> 18:00.000
Let's turn to the slide and get acquainted with the definition.

18:00.000 --> 18:03.000
What is group dynamics?

18:03.000 --> 18:08.000
Group dynamics is the designation, unlike the group statics,

18:08.000 --> 18:14.000
of a set of dynamic processes that occur simultaneously in a group

18:14.000 --> 18:16.000
for a certain period of time,

18:16.000 --> 18:21.000
and which are the movement of the group from stage to stage,

18:21.000 --> 18:23.000
that is, its development.

18:23.000 --> 18:29.000
Well, probably, it is not a secret for any of you that movement is life,

18:29.000 --> 18:32.000
and a person develops only by means of movement.

18:33.000 --> 18:41.000
Let's try to observe how the development of a group or a team occurs.

18:41.000 --> 18:45.000
We will consider this on the model of Tuckman,

18:45.000 --> 18:47.000
the most popular model in business,

18:47.000 --> 18:49.000
which is often used,

18:49.000 --> 18:54.000
which outlined the four main stages of the development of a group,

18:54.000 --> 18:56.000
the development of a team.

18:57.000 --> 19:00.000
Please pay attention to the proposed slide.

19:01.000 --> 19:07.000
You may notice that there is an uneven distribution of the graph,

19:07.000 --> 19:13.000
and it moves not along the rising, but along the descending trajectory.

19:14.000 --> 19:19.000
So, the first stage of the development of a team is formation.

19:20.000 --> 19:25.000
What is formation of a team relative to those criteria

19:25.000 --> 19:28.000
that we have just considered in detail?

19:28.000 --> 19:31.000
At the stage of formation of a team,

19:31.000 --> 19:37.000
people treat each other very carefully and carefully.

19:37.000 --> 19:40.000
People look at each other,

19:40.000 --> 19:43.000
make a conscious or unconscious choice

19:43.000 --> 19:46.000
who they are with, why they are there,

19:46.000 --> 19:48.000
whom they trust in the team

19:48.000 --> 19:51.000
— it is not a team yet, in a group —

19:51.000 --> 19:53.000
whom they do not trust.

19:53.000 --> 19:57.000
What happens at the stage of formation of a group?

19:58.000 --> 20:01.000
There are no clearly defined goals,

20:01.000 --> 20:04.000
there are no clearly distributed roles,

20:04.000 --> 20:07.000
interpersonal communications are not built,

20:07.000 --> 20:10.000
despite the fact that there are no conflicts in the group,

20:10.000 --> 20:13.000
the group exists quite calmly,

20:13.000 --> 20:16.000
however, there are hidden, yet unexpressed conflicts

20:16.000 --> 20:20.000
within each employee, within each individual.

20:20.000 --> 20:24.000
I repeat, people treat each other politely,

20:24.000 --> 20:27.000
but this is a signal for you, as for the leader,

20:27.000 --> 20:30.000
to think that politeness at the stage of formation of a team

20:30.000 --> 20:32.000
is not a success,

20:32.000 --> 20:36.000
it is a behavior, a natural behavior of a person

20:36.000 --> 20:40.000
who is still making a conscious choice

20:40.000 --> 20:43.000
who he is going with, what he is going for,

20:43.000 --> 20:46.000
and why he is doing it.

20:46.000 --> 20:49.000
So, at the stage of formation,

20:49.000 --> 20:52.000
there is a certain style of management.

20:52.000 --> 20:55.000
I think you, as a leader,

20:55.000 --> 21:00.000
should learn this style as a rigid and directive one.

21:00.000 --> 21:03.000
At this stage, the leader is a bright,

21:03.000 --> 21:06.000
pronounced leader.

21:06.000 --> 21:09.000
The style of management is directive,

21:09.000 --> 21:12.000
the tasks are clearly set, there is clear control.

21:12.000 --> 21:15.000
There is no place for delegating powers

21:15.000 --> 21:18.000
and opportunities to interact,

21:18.000 --> 21:21.000
consult and ask.

21:21.000 --> 21:24.000
The leader positions himself as a leader

21:24.000 --> 21:28.000
so that at the next stages of the development of the team

21:28.000 --> 21:31.000
it is easier for him to manage,

21:31.000 --> 21:34.000
and the next stages will be more difficult.

21:34.000 --> 21:37.000
The task of the leader is to provide all the resources

21:37.000 --> 21:40.000
for the comfortable functioning of the team.

21:40.000 --> 21:45.000
Here you can recall the motivational model of MacGregor

21:45.000 --> 21:48.000
or Herzberg, who said that until you satisfy

21:48.000 --> 21:51.000
the basic hygiene needs of a person,

21:51.000 --> 21:54.000
they will feel anger.

21:54.000 --> 21:57.000
But if you satisfy these basic hygiene needs of a person,

21:57.000 --> 22:00.000
such as working conditions,

22:00.000 --> 22:03.000
decent salary, airy hygiene,

22:03.000 --> 22:06.000
and the ability to eat during lunch,

22:06.000 --> 22:09.000
if you satisfy these criteria of the employees,

22:09.000 --> 22:12.000
it does not mean that they will work better.

22:12.000 --> 22:15.000
They will simply lack the feeling of dissatisfaction

22:16.000 --> 22:19.000
or, as I said, the feeling of anger.

22:19.000 --> 22:22.000
It is very important for you as a leader

22:22.000 --> 22:25.000
not to meet once a quarter with your employees,

22:25.000 --> 22:28.000
as I told you in the previous example,

22:28.000 --> 22:31.000
but to make these meetings as often as possible.

22:31.000 --> 22:34.000
The smallest, simplest,

22:34.000 --> 22:37.000
the most inconspicuous achievements

22:37.000 --> 22:40.000
must be supported and praised by the employees.

22:40.000 --> 22:43.000
The smallest, I emphasize,

22:44.000 --> 22:47.000
because at the last stages of the development of the team

22:47.000 --> 22:50.000
these achievements will be more large-scale.

22:50.000 --> 22:53.000
And for such small achievements,

22:53.000 --> 22:56.000
which you praise at the stage of formation,

22:56.000 --> 22:59.000
it will no longer be a motivation for the employees.

22:59.000 --> 23:02.000
So, after you go through the stage of formation,

23:02.000 --> 23:05.000
the storm stage comes.

23:05.000 --> 23:08.000
This is one of the most difficult periods

23:08.000 --> 23:11.000
in the development of the team, in the dynamics of the group,

23:12.000 --> 23:15.000
when people begin to express their emotions openly.

23:15.000 --> 23:18.000
At this stage, there are a lot of conflicts in the group,

23:18.000 --> 23:21.000
aggressiveness is very high,

23:21.000 --> 23:24.000
people do not agree with their colleagues,

23:24.000 --> 23:27.000
people express confrontation

23:27.000 --> 23:30.000
with any ideas.

23:30.000 --> 23:33.000
It is very important for you as a leader

23:33.000 --> 23:36.000
to learn how to manage a conflict situation

23:36.000 --> 23:39.000
and manage it in a way

23:40.000 --> 23:43.000
that does not mean to prohibit expressing your opinion,

23:43.000 --> 23:46.000
to prohibit arguing or to prohibit being aggressive.

23:46.000 --> 23:49.000
I mean aggressiveness in the permissible limits,

23:49.000 --> 23:52.000
when employees do not throw cups or phones at each other,

23:52.000 --> 23:55.000
but aggressiveness at the level of constructive emotions.

23:55.000 --> 23:58.000
Your task at this stage,

23:58.000 --> 24:01.000
within the framework of managing the conflict,

24:01.000 --> 24:04.000
is, on the contrary,

24:04.000 --> 24:07.000
to support aggressive emotions

24:08.000 --> 24:11.000
and to pull them out of people,

24:11.000 --> 24:14.000
to get them to express their disagreement

24:14.000 --> 24:17.000
or their opinion openly and freely.

24:17.000 --> 24:20.000
This is the main key task of the leader

24:20.000 --> 24:23.000
at the storm stage.

24:23.000 --> 24:26.000
It is clear that we are approaching

24:26.000 --> 24:29.000
a different style of management.

24:29.000 --> 24:32.000
If we said that at the stage of formation

24:32.000 --> 24:35.000
you are direct and tough,

24:36.000 --> 24:39.000
you just say, set tasks and demand their execution,

24:39.000 --> 24:42.000
then at the stage of management,

24:42.000 --> 24:45.000
when conflicts arise,

24:45.000 --> 24:48.000
people begin to express their opinion openly.

24:48.000 --> 24:51.000
Here your task is not just to set goals or tasks,

24:51.000 --> 24:54.000
but to explain to people why this is happening,

24:54.000 --> 24:57.000
why each of them needs it.

24:57.000 --> 25:00.000
As for the control function,

25:00.000 --> 25:03.000
if at the stage of formation

25:03.000 --> 25:06.000
the control function is total,

25:06.000 --> 25:09.000
then at the storm stage the control function is step-by-step,

25:09.000 --> 25:12.000
that is, after a certain period of time.

25:12.000 --> 25:15.000
People should understand that you give them an opportunity

25:15.000 --> 25:18.000
to express themselves within the framework of this group.

25:22.000 --> 25:25.000
And I repeat,

25:25.000 --> 25:28.000
it is necessary to provoke an open explanation of the relationship.

25:28.000 --> 25:31.000
This is very useful,

25:32.000 --> 25:35.000
because if at this stage you forbid people

25:35.000 --> 25:38.000
with policies, procedures, rules and norms of behavior

25:38.000 --> 25:41.000
an open explanation of relations,

25:41.000 --> 25:44.000
it will definitely emerge at the next stage,

25:44.000 --> 25:47.000
and you simply will not be able to go from the third stage

25:47.000 --> 25:50.000
to the fourth stage.

25:50.000 --> 25:53.000
You will have to return to the storm stage.

25:53.000 --> 25:56.000
We will look at this further.

25:56.000 --> 25:59.000
So, the storm stage is when people have agreed,

25:59.000 --> 26:02.000
when they understood and saw you not only as a tough leader,

26:02.000 --> 26:05.000
but also as a leader who advises,

26:05.000 --> 26:08.000
explains and agrees on priorities.

26:08.000 --> 26:11.000
Your team comfortably moves to the next stage of its development,

26:11.000 --> 26:14.000
which we call normalization.

26:14.000 --> 26:17.000
What is the difference between this stage and the previous two?

26:17.000 --> 26:20.000
I have already said that the main key moment

26:20.000 --> 26:23.000
when people start to understand each other

26:23.000 --> 26:26.000
and understand each other's needs

26:26.000 --> 26:29.000
is when people start to calm down.

26:29.000 --> 26:32.000
Negative emotions are replaced by positive ones.

26:32.000 --> 26:35.000
People begin to trust each other more.

26:35.000 --> 26:38.000
And now all the decisions they discuss and make

26:38.000 --> 26:41.000
are not painted with such a dark stain of negativity

26:41.000 --> 26:44.000
as it was at the storm stage.

26:44.000 --> 26:47.000
This is very important.

26:47.000 --> 26:50.000
And you, as a leader, must remember this.

26:50.000 --> 26:53.000
At this stage, norms and rules are formed.

26:54.000 --> 26:57.000
When people have calmed down,

26:57.000 --> 27:00.000
when they have worked out all their emotions,

27:00.000 --> 27:03.000
it is time for logic.

27:03.000 --> 27:06.000
People begin to develop standards of interaction,

27:06.000 --> 27:09.000
to develop norms and rules of life.

27:09.000 --> 27:12.000
They are distributed spontaneously.

27:12.000 --> 27:15.000
The roles of the team's interaction are distributed.

